cs.CL, cs.AI, cs.LG, cs.IR, cs.NE. 

The paper proposes a neural machine-reading model that constructs dynamic knowledge graphs from procedural text, which involves natural language processing and machine learning techniques. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.CL (Computation and Language). Additionally, the model uses machine reading comprehension (MRC) to query for entity states, which falls under the sub-category of cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). The model also uses recurrent neural networks (RNNs) to build the knowledge graphs, which is a common technique in the sub-category of cs.LG (Machine Learning). The model's ability to track evolving states of participant entities suggests it may also fall under the sub-category of cs.IR (Information Retrieval). Finally, the paper presents evidence that the model's knowledge graphs help it to impose commonsense constraints on its predictions, which is a topic of interest in the sub-category of cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing).
